INSERT INTO public.blog_posts
  (slug, title, meta_description, featured_image_url, content, status, is_published, language, published_at, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES
  (
    'how-many-calories-in-chicken',
    'How Many Calories in Chicken? Complete Nutrition Guide',
    'Discover how many calories are in chicken breast, thigh, wings & more. Compare grilled vs fried, plus tips for low-calorie chicken dishes.',
    'https://smsikaqybxtnzjvruhsa.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/blog-images/compressed-1767911587781.webp',
    $body$<div><h2>How Many Calories in Chicken? Complete Nutrition Guide</h2><p>Chicken is the most popular protein source in the world for good reason. It's affordable, versatile, lean, and delicious. Whether you prefer grilled chicken breast, crispy fried wings, or slow-roasted thighs, understanding chicken's calorie content can help you make smarter dietary choices.</p><p>In this guide, we'll break down how many calories are in different cuts of chicken, compare cooking methods, and share tips for enjoying chicken while managing your calorie intake.</p><hr><h2>Basic Chicken Calories by Cut</h2><p>Not all chicken is equal when it comes to calories. The cut you choose makes a big difference in calorie and fat content.</p><div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Cut</th><th>Skinless (per 3.5 oz)</th><th>With Skin (per 3.5 oz)</th><th>Protein</th><th>Fat (skinless)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Breast</td><td>165 cal</td><td>~215 cal</td><td>31g</td><td>3.6g</td></tr><tr><td>Thigh</td><td>209 cal</td><td>229 cal</td><td>26g</td><td>10.9g</td></tr><tr><td>Drumstick</td><td>~155 cal</td><td>~175 cal</td><td>23g</td><td>7.4g</td></tr><tr><td>Wing</td><td>~203 cal</td><td>~290 cal</td><td>30g</td><td>8.1g</td></tr><tr><td>Whole chicken (mixed)</td><td>190 cal</td><td>239 cal</td><td>27g</td><td>7.4g</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h3>Chicken Breast</h3><p>Chicken breast is the leanest and most popular cut for health-conscious eaters. A 3.5-ounce (100-gram) serving of cooked skinless chicken breast contains about 165 calories, 31 grams of protein, and only 3.6 grams of fat. This gives it one of the best protein-to-calorie ratios among foods.</p><p>A typical medium-sized cooked chicken breast weighs about 6-8 ounces and provides 280-370 calories. Keeping the skin on adds about 50-80 calories per breast from the extra fat.</p><h3>Chicken Thigh</h3><p>Chicken thighs are darker meat with more fat and flavor than breasts. A 3.5-ounce serving of cooked skinless chicken thigh contains about 209 calories, 26 grams of protein, and 10.9 grams of fat. With skin, the same portion has about 229 calories.</p><p>One cooked bone-in chicken thigh with skin weighs about 4 ounces and contains roughly 230-280 calories. Boneless skinless thighs are slightly lower at about 180-210 calories each.</p><h3>Chicken Drumstick</h3><p>Drumsticks are a favorite for their flavor and convenience. A cooked drumstick with skin contains about 112 calories and 14 grams of protein. Without skin, a drumstick has about 76 calories.</p><p>If you eat multiple drumsticks, the calories add up quickly. Three drumsticks with skin provide about 336 calories.</p><h3>Chicken Wing</h3><p>Wings are the highest-calorie cut of chicken for their size. A cooked chicken wing with skin contains about 99 calories. Most wing preparations add more calories through breading and sauce.</p><p>A restaurant serving of 10 buffalo wings contains 800-1,200 calories, depending on the sauce and breading. Dry-rubbed or plain wings are the lowest-calorie option at about 80-100 calories per wing.</p><h3>Whole Chicken</h3><p>A whole roasted chicken provides different nutrition depending on which parts you eat. On average, 3.5 ounces of mixed roasted chicken meat with skin contains about 239 calories. The same portion without skin has about 190 calories.</p><p>A 3-pound whole chicken yields about 1.5 pounds of edible meat, providing roughly 1,100-1,400 calories total depending on whether you eat the skin.</p><hr><h2>Calories by Cooking Method</h2><p>How you prepare chicken greatly affects its calorie content. The same chicken breast can range from 165 to over 400 calories, depending on how you cook it.</p><div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Cooking Method</th><th>Calories (per 3.5 oz breast)</th><th>Added Fat Needed</th><th>Key Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Poached or Boiled</td><td>165</td><td>None</td><td>Lowest calorie; no added fat required</td></tr><tr><td>Grilled</td><td>165–185</td><td>Minimal</td><td>Excess fat drips away during cooking</td></tr><tr><td>Baked (no fat added)</td><td>165–180</td><td>None</td><td>Similar to grilled; easy to batch cook</td></tr><tr><td>Air-Fried</td><td>180–220</td><td>Minimal spray</td><td>Crispy exterior with much less fat than frying</td></tr><tr><td>Pan-Fried (cooking spray)</td><td>180–200</td><td>Spray only</td><td>Non-stick pan reduces fat needed</td></tr><tr><td>Pan-Fried (1 tbsp oil)</td><td>220–260</td><td>1 tbsp oil</td><td>Absorbs some fat; 30–50% more than grilled</td></tr><tr><td>Baked (with 1 tbsp oil/butter)</td><td>200–230</td><td>1 tbsp fat</td><td>Adds ~120 cal per tbsp to batch</td></tr><tr><td>Breaded, Deep-Fried</td><td>260–320</td><td>Full submersion</td><td>Breading doubles fat absorption</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h3>Grilled Chicken</h3><p>Grilling is one of the healthiest ways to cook chicken. A grilled skinless chicken breast contains about 165-185 calories per 3.5 ounces, with minimal added fat since excess drips away during cooking. Marinating in oil-based sauces adds 20-50 calories depending on how much marinade stays on the meat.</p><p>Grilled chicken thighs contain about 200-230 calories per 3.5 ounces. The higher fat content keeps them moist during grilling without added oil.</p><h3>Baked or Roasted Chicken</h3><p>Baked chicken breast without added fat contains about 165-180 calories per 3.5 ounces, similar to grilled. Roasting a whole chicken with skin yields approximately 190-240 calories per 3.5 ounces, depending on whether you eat the crispy skin.</p><p>Roasting with olive oil or butter adds calories. One tablespoon of olive oil adds 120 calories, though only some is absorbed into the meat.</p><h3>Pan-Fried Chicken</h3><p>Pan-frying chicken in oil adds significant calories. A pan-fried chicken breast cooked in one tablespoon of oil contains about 220-260 calories per 3.5 ounces. The chicken absorbs some of the fat, increasing calories by 30-50% compared to grilled.</p><p>Using a non-stick pan with cooking spray can keep pan-fried chicken at around 180-200 calories per serving.</p><h3>Deep-Fried Chicken</h3><p>Deep-fried chicken is the highest-calorie preparation method. A 3.5-ounce serving of breaded, deep-fried chicken breast contains approximately 260-320 calories. Fried chicken thighs and drumsticks are even higher in fat.</p><p>The breading absorbs oil during frying, sometimes doubling the calories compared to the same cut without breading. A piece of KFC Original Recipe fried chicken breast contains about 390 calories.</p><h3>Poached or Boiled Chicken</h3><p>Poaching or boiling chicken is the lowest-calorie cooking method. Poached chicken breast contains about 165 calories per 3.5 ounces with no added fat. This method is popular for chicken salad or shredded chicken for tacos and soups.</p><p>Poached chicken can be bland without proper seasoning. Adding herbs, garlic, and aromatics to the poaching liquid enhances flavor without adding calories.</p><h3>Air-Fried Chicken</h3><p>Air frying has become popular as a healthier alternative to deep frying. Air-fried chicken breast contains approximately 180-220 calories per 3.5 ounces, depending on whether breading is used. This is significantly less than deep-fried chicken while still providing a crispy exterior.</p><p>Air-fried chicken wings contain about 100-130 calories per wing, compared to 150-200 for fried wings.</p><hr><h2>Popular Chicken Dishes and Their Calories</h2><p>Understanding chicken dishes helps you make informed choices when cooking at home or dining out.</p><div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Dish</th><th>Serving</th><th>Calories</th><th>Main Calorie Factor</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Plain grilled chicken breast</td><td>4 oz</td><td>185–220</td><td>Lean base — minimal added fat</td></tr><tr><td>Rotisserie chicken breast (no skin)</td><td>3.5 oz</td><td>140–160</td><td>Convenient; watch sodium content</td></tr><tr><td>Rotisserie chicken quarter (thigh &amp; leg)</td><td>1 quarter</td><td>300–400</td><td>Highest-calorie quarter</td></tr><tr><td>Chicken stir-fry (home)</td><td>1 cup</td><td>250–350</td><td>Controlled oil amount</td></tr><tr><td>Chicken stir-fry (restaurant)</td><td>1 cup</td><td>300–600</td><td>More oil than home-cooked</td></tr><tr><td>Indian butter chicken</td><td>1 serving</td><td>400–600</td><td>Cream and butter in sauce</td></tr><tr><td>Thai green or red curry</td><td>1 serving</td><td>350–500</td><td>Coconut milk base</td></tr><tr><td>Chicken salad (with mayo)</td><td>1 cup</td><td>350–450</td><td>Mayonnaise is main calorie source</td></tr><tr><td>Chicken salad (Greek yogurt)</td><td>1 cup</td><td>200–280</td><td>Lighter swap, same creaminess</td></tr><tr><td>Grilled chicken salad (light dressing)</td><td>1 plate</td><td>300–400</td><td>Lean option</td></tr><tr><td>Restaurant chicken salad (loaded)</td><td>1 plate</td><td>800–1,200</td><td>Cheese, bacon, croutons, creamy dressing</td></tr><tr><td>Chicken noodle soup</td><td>1 cup</td><td>150–200</td><td>Broth-based, naturally low calorie</td></tr><tr><td>Grilled chicken taco (simple)</td><td>1 taco</td><td>150–200</td><td>Salsa and lettuce only</td></tr><tr><td>Chicken taco (loaded)</td><td>1 taco</td><td>250–350</td><td>Cheese, sour cream, guacamole</td></tr><tr><td>Grilled chicken sandwich (basic)</td><td>1 sandwich</td><td>350–450</td><td>Bun and basic toppings</td></tr><tr><td>Loaded chicken sandwich</td><td>1 sandwich</td><td>600–800</td><td>Mayo, cheese, bacon added</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h3>Rotisserie Chicken</h3><p>A store-bought rotisserie chicken is a convenient option for busy families. The breast meat without skin contains about 140-160 calories per 3.5 ounces, while thigh meat with skin has approximately 200-230 calories. A quarter of a typical rotisserie chicken provides 250-400 calories, depending on which quarter you choose.</p><p>The breast quarter is lowest in calories, while the thigh and leg quarter is highest. Removing the skin saves about 30-50 calories per serving.</p><h3>Chicken Stir-Fry</h3><p>A chicken stir-fry with vegetables contains about 300-450 calories per cup, depending on the oil used. Restaurant stir-fries often have more oil than homemade, pushing calories to 500-600 per serving.</p><p>Making stir-fry at home with minimal oil and plenty of vegetables keeps calories around 250-350 per serving.</p><h3>Chicken Curry</h3><p>Chicken curry calories vary dramatically based on the type and preparation. A serving of Indian butter chicken contains approximately 400-600 calories due to the cream and butter in the sauce. Thai green or red curry with coconut milk has about 350-500 calories per serving.</p><p>Lighter curries made with tomato-based sauces or light coconut milk contain approximately 250-350 calories per serving.</p><h3>Chicken Salad</h3><p>Traditional chicken salad with mayonnaise contains about 350-450 calories per cup. The mayonnaise provides most of the calories and fat. A chicken salad sandwich on bread adds another 150-200 calories.</p><p>Healthier versions made with Greek yogurt instead of mayo contain about 200-280 calories per cup while still providing creamy texture and good flavor.</p><p>A grilled chicken salad with mixed greens and light dressing is one of the lowest-calorie chicken meals. A generous salad with 4 ounces of grilled chicken, vegetables, and two tablespoons of vinaigrette contains approximately 300-400 calories.</p><p>However, restaurant chicken salads can be calorie bombs. Adding cheese, croutons, bacon, and creamy dressing can push a "healthy" salad to 800-1,200 calories.</p><h3>Chicken Soup</h3><p>Homemade chicken soup is low in calories. A cup of chicken noodle soup contains about 150-200 calories, while chicken vegetable soup has about 100-150 calories. The broth base keeps calories low while providing warmth and nutrition.</p><p>Cream-based chicken soups, such as chicken pot pie filling or cream of chicken soup, contain 250-400 calories per cup due to the added cream and butter.</p><h3>Chicken Tacos</h3><p>Chicken tacos vary widely in calories depending on preparation and toppings. A simple grilled chicken taco with salsa and lettuce contains about 150-200 calories. Adding cheese, sour cream, and guacamole increases the count to 250-350 per taco.</p><p>Restaurant chicken tacos, especially those with fried shells or crispy chicken, can contain 300-450 calories each.</p><h3>Chicken Sandwich</h3><p>A basic grilled chicken sandwich contains approximately 350-450 calories, depending on the bun and toppings. Adding mayo, cheese, and bacon can push a chicken sandwich to 600-800 calories.</p><p>Fast food grilled chicken sandwiches range from 320 calories for simple options to over 700 calories for premium versions with special sauces and toppings.</p><hr><h2>Fast Food Chicken Calories</h2><p>Fast-food chicken varies widely in calories. Here's what to expect at popular chains.</p><div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Item</th><th>Chain</th><th>Calories</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Grilled Chicken Sandwich</td><td>Chick-fil-A</td><td>320</td><td>One of the healthiest fast food options</td></tr><tr><td>Grilled Chicken Sandwich</td><td>Wendy's</td><td>370</td><td>Reasonable grilled choice</td></tr><tr><td>Artisan Grilled Chicken Sandwich</td><td>McDonald's</td><td>380</td><td>Grilled, not fried</td></tr><tr><td>Grilled Nuggets (8-count)</td><td>Chick-fil-A</td><td>140</td><td>vs 260 cal for fried version</td></tr><tr><td>Original Recipe Chicken Breast</td><td>KFC</td><td>390</td><td>Classic Southern fried</td></tr><tr><td>Classic Chicken Sandwich (fried)</td><td>Chick-fil-A</td><td>440</td><td>Fan favourite fried sandwich</td></tr><tr><td>Chicken Sandwich (fried)</td><td>Popeyes</td><td>700</td><td>Among the highest-calorie sandwiches</td></tr><tr><td>10 Buffalo Wings + medium sauce</td><td>Buffalo Wild Wings</td><td>1,000–1,200</td><td>Sauce adds significantly to base wing</td></tr><tr><td>10 Wings (dry rub)</td><td>Buffalo Wild Wings</td><td>700–800</td><td>Lowest-calorie wing option</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h3>Grilled Options</h3><p>Chick-fil-A's Grilled Chicken Sandwich contains 320 calories, making it one of the healthier fast food options. Wendy's Grilled Chicken Sandwich has about 370 calories. McDonald's Artisan Grilled Chicken Sandwich contains 380 calories.</p><p>Grilled chicken nuggets at Chick-fil-A contain only 140 calories for an 8-count serving, compared to 260 calories for regular fried nuggets.</p><h3>Fried Options</h3><p>KFC's Original Recipe Chicken Breast contains 390 calories per piece. Popeyes Chicken Sandwich, famous for starting the chicken sandwich wars, contains 700 calories. Chick-fil-A's classic fried chicken sandwich has 440 calories.</p><p>Chicken tenders and strips usually contain 150-250 calories per piece, depending on size and breading thickness. A 4-piece chicken tender meal with fries and dipping sauce can exceed 1,000 calories.</p><h3>Wings</h3><p>At Buffalo Wild Wings, traditional wings contain about 90-100 calories per wing before sauce. Sauces add significantly, with creamy, sweet sauces contributing the most calories.</p><p>A 10-wing order with medium buffalo sauce contains approximately 1,000-1,200 calories. Dry rubs are the lowest-calorie option at about 70-80 calories per wing.</p><hr><h2>Chicken and Weight Loss</h2><p>Chicken, particularly chicken breast, is considered one of the best foods for weight loss and muscle building.</p><h3>High Protein, Low Calorie</h3><p>Chicken breast provides exceptional protein density. With 31 grams of protein per 165 calories, it offers more protein per calorie than almost any other whole food. This high protein helps preserve muscle during weight loss and keeps you full longer.</p><div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Protein Source</th><th>Calories (per 3.5 oz)</th><th>Protein</th><th>Fat</th><th>Best For</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Chicken breast (skinless)</td><td>165</td><td>31g</td><td>3.6g</td><td>Best protein-to-calorie ratio</td></tr><tr><td>Turkey breast (skinless)</td><td>135</td><td>30g</td><td>1g</td><td>Even leaner than chicken</td></tr><tr><td>Tuna (canned in water)</td><td>109</td><td>25g</td><td>0.5g</td><td>Lowest calorie high-protein option</td></tr><tr><td>Pork tenderloin</td><td>143</td><td>26g</td><td>3.5g</td><td>Comparable leanness to chicken</td></tr><tr><td>Salmon</td><td>208</td><td>20g</td><td>13g</td><td>Omega-3s; heart-healthy fats</td></tr><tr><td>Lean ground beef (90%)</td><td>218</td><td>26g</td><td>13g</td><td>More fat, richer flavor</td></tr><tr><td>Eggs (2 large)</td><td>156</td><td>12g</td><td>10.5g</td><td>Complete protein, versatile</td></tr><tr><td>Firm tofu</td><td>76</td><td>8g</td><td>4g</td><td>Plant-based, lowest calories</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h3>Versatility</h3><p>Chicken can be prepared in many ways, preventing diet boredom. You can enjoy it grilled, baked, stir-fried, in soups, salads, wraps, and more. This versatility makes it easier to stick to a calorie-controlled diet long-term.</p><h3>Satiety</h3><p>Protein is the most satiating macronutrient, and chicken is mostly protein. Studies show that high-protein meals reduce hunger and decrease overall calorie intake throughout the day. Eating chicken for lunch can help prevent afternoon snacking and overeating at dinner.</p><h3>Meal Prep Friendly</h3><p>Chicken is ideal for meal prepping. You can grill or bake several pounds of chicken breast at once and portion it for the week. Having pre-cooked chicken available makes it easier to choose healthy options when you're busy or tired.</p><hr><h2>Chicken Skin: To Eat or Not to Eat?</h2><p>The question of whether to eat chicken skin is common among health-conscious eaters.</p><p>Chicken skin adds about 30-50 calories per ounce and significantly increases fat content. A chicken breast with skin contains about 50% more calories than the same breast without skin. The skin also has more saturated fat than the meat.</p><div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Cut</th><th>Without Skin</th><th>With Skin</th><th>Extra Calories</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Breast (per 3.5 oz)</td><td>165</td><td>~215</td><td>~50</td><td>Skin adds ~11g extra fat</td></tr><tr><td>Thigh (per 3.5 oz)</td><td>209</td><td>229</td><td>~20</td><td>Smaller difference due to dark meat</td></tr><tr><td>Whole chicken (per 3.5 oz)</td><td>190</td><td>239</td><td>~49</td><td>Eating mixed cuts with skin</td></tr><tr><td>Drumstick (whole piece)</td><td>~76</td><td>~112</td><td>~36</td><td>Easy to remove before eating</td></tr><tr><td>Wing (whole piece)</td><td>~65</td><td>~99</td><td>~34</td><td>Skin tightly bound — hardest to remove</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>However, chicken skin does provide some benefits. It keeps the meat moist during cooking and adds flavor. The fat in chicken skin is about 30% saturated and 70% unsaturated, which is better than many people assume. For most people watching calories, removing the skin is an easy way to reduce intake. Occasionally enjoying chicken with skin won't derail a healthy diet, especially if you account for the extra calories.</p><hr><h2>Tips for Reducing Chicken Dish Calories</h2><p>Here are practical strategies for enjoying chicken while keeping calories in check.</p><div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Strategy</th><th>Calories Saved</th><th>How to Apply</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Choose breast over thigh</td><td>~40–60 per 3.5 oz</td><td>Swap dark meat for white meat</td></tr><tr><td>Remove the skin</td><td>~30–80 per piece</td><td>Pull off before or after cooking</td></tr><tr><td>Grill or bake vs deep-fry</td><td>~100–200 per serving</td><td>Avoid breading and frying oil entirely</td></tr><tr><td>Cooking spray vs butter</td><td>~100 per serving</td><td>1 tbsp butter = 100 cal; spray = near zero</td></tr><tr><td>Hot sauce vs creamy dressing</td><td>~100–250 per serving</td><td>Swap ranch or mayo-based sauces</td></tr><tr><td>50% vegetables in stir-fry</td><td>~100–150 per meal</td><td>Double vegetables, reduce chicken volume</td></tr><tr><td>Home-cooked vs restaurant</td><td>~150–250 per meal</td><td>Control oil, portions, and sauces yourself</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h3>Choose Breast Over Thigh</h3><p>Swapping thighs for breast meat saves approximately 40-60 calories per 3.5-ounce serving. While thighs have more flavor, the calorie difference adds up over time.</p><h3>Remove the Skin</h3><p>Removing chicken skin before or after cooking saves 30-80 calories per piece, depending on the cut. If you love crispy skin, eat it occasionally as a treat rather than daily.</p><h3>Grill, Bake, or Air Fry</h3><p>These cooking methods require minimal added fat compared to pan-frying or deep-frying. The calorie difference between grilled and fried chicken can be 100-200 calories per serving.</p><h3>Watch Your Portions</h3><p>A healthy portion of chicken is 3-4 ounces cooked, about the size of a deck of cards. Restaurant portions are often 6-8 ounces or more. Being mindful of portions can cut your chicken calories in half.</p><h3>Be Careful with Sauces</h3><p>Sauces and dressings can add 100-300 calories to an otherwise healthy chicken dish. BBQ sauce, teriyaki glaze, honey mustard, and creamy sauces are especially calorie-dense. Use them sparingly or choose lighter options like hot sauce, salsa, or lemon juice.</p><h3>Load Up on Vegetables</h3><p>When making chicken dishes, use more vegetables and less chicken to reduce calories while maintaining volume. A stir-fry with 50% vegetables and 50% chicken has fewer calories than one that's mostly chicken.</p><hr><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2><p><strong>Is chicken healthier than beef?</strong></p><p>Chicken breast is lower in calories and saturated fat than most beef cuts. A 3.5-ounce serving of chicken breast has 165 calories compared to 250 for lean ground beef. Both can be part of a healthy diet when eaten in appropriate portions.</p><p><strong>How much chicken should I eat per day?</strong></p><p>Most nutrition guidelines suggest 3-6 ounces of protein per meal. For chicken, this means 1-2 palm-sized portions per day, or about 6-12 ounces total. Athletes and those building muscle may eat more.</p><p><strong>Does organic chicken have fewer calories?</strong></p><p>No, organic chicken has the same calories as conventional chicken. The difference is in how the chickens are raised, not the nutritional content.</p><p><strong>Is rotisserie chicken healthy?</strong></p><p>Rotisserie chicken can be a healthy choice, especially if you choose breast meat and remove the skin. Watch for high sodium, as many rotisserie chickens are brined or seasoned with salt.</p><p><strong>What's the healthiest way to eat chicken?</strong></p><p>Grilled, baked, or poached skinless chicken breast with vegetables is the healthiest preparation. This maximizes protein while minimizing calories, fat, and sodium.</p><hr><h2>Track Your Chicken Calories with CalorieVision</h2><p>Want to know exactly how many calories are in your chicken dish? CalorieVision's AI-powered photo analysis can instantly calculate the calories in any chicken meal, from a grilled breast to a loaded chicken burrito. Simply snap a photo and get accurate nutritional information in seconds.</p><p><strong>Try CalorieVision free</strong> and take the guesswork out of tracking chicken calories.</p><hr><h2>Conclusion</h2><p>Chicken is one of the most nutritious and versatile protein sources available. A 3.5-ounce serving of skinless chicken breast contains 165 calories and 31 grams of protein, making it ideal for weight loss and muscle building. The calorie content of chicken varies based on the cut and cooking method. Breast meat is the leanest, while thighs and wings have more fat and calories. Grilling and baking keep calories low, while breading and deep-frying can more than double the calorie count.</p><p>By choosing lean cuts, using healthy cooking methods, and being mindful of portions and sauces, you can enjoy chicken dishes while maintaining your health and fitness goals.</p></div>$body$,
