INSERT INTO public.blog_posts
  (slug, title, meta_description, featured_image_url, content, status, is_published, language, published_at, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES
  (
    'watermelon-calories-complete-guide',
    'Watermelon Calories: The Refreshing Truth About This Summer Favorite',
    'Discover the calories in watermelon - per cup, per slice, and per wedge. Plus hydration benefits, lycopene content, and weight loss tips.',
    'https://smsikaqybxtnzjvruhsa.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/blog-images/featured-1768517554325.webp',
    $body$<div><h2>Watermelon Calories: The Refreshing Truth About This Summer Favorite</h2><p>Few foods capture the feeling of summer like watermelon. Its sweet taste, bright color, and hydrating qualities make it a favorite around the world. If you're watching your health, you'll be glad to know watermelon is low in calories and packed with nutrition. Here's what you need to know about watermelon calories.</p><hr><h2>Impressively Low Calorie Content</h2><p>A cup of diced watermelon has about 46 calories. This makes it one of the lowest-calorie fruits, so you can enjoy a generous serving without worrying about too many calories.</p><p>A classic watermelon wedge, like the kind you'd eat at a summer barbecue, has about 86 calories if it's one inch thick. Even a big slice like this is still low in calories.</p><p>One hundred grams of watermelon provides only about 30 calories, among the lowest of any fruit per weight. This metric helps when comparing watermelon to other fruits or tracking intake precisely.</p><p>A whole mini watermelon, which weighs about 5 pounds and has about 3 pounds of edible fruit, contains about 410 calories. Most people wouldn't eat a whole mini watermelon by themselves, but this shows you can eat a lot of watermelon for not many calories.</p><p>Most of the calories in watermelon come from carbohydrates, with about 11 grams per cup. There's very little protein or fat. Of those carbs, about 9 grams are natural sugars.</p><div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Serving</th><th>Calories</th><th>Carbs</th><th>Sugar</th><th>Water Content</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1 cup diced (152g)</td><td>46</td><td>11g</td><td>9g</td><td>92%</td></tr><tr><td>1-inch wedge (~286g)</td><td>86</td><td>22g</td><td>18g</td><td>92%</td></tr><tr><td>100g</td><td>30</td><td>7.5g</td><td>6g</td><td>92%</td></tr><tr><td>2 cups (generous serving)</td><td>92</td><td>22g</td><td>18g</td><td>92%</td></tr><tr><td>Whole mini watermelon (~5 lbs)</td><td>~410</td><td>~100g</td><td>~84g</td><td>92%</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr><h2>Why Watermelon Is So Low in Calories</h2><p>Watermelon gets its name for a reason—it's about 92% water. This high water content means it has very few calories for its size.</p><p>If you compare watermelon to other fruits, a medium banana has about 105 calories, an apple has 95, and a cup of grapes has 62. Watermelon's 46 calories per cup are lower than those of almost all other fruits.</p><p>Because watermelon is mostly water, you can eat a big, filling portion for fewer calories than you'd get from a smaller serving of heavier foods. This makes it a great choice if you want to feel satisfied without eating too many calories.</p><p>Watermelon does have sugar, but not as much as you might think. Even though it tastes very sweet, it actually has less sugar per serving than some fruits that don't taste as sweet. Its fresh, clean flavor makes it seem sweeter than it really is.</p><div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Fruit</th><th>Calories / Cup</th><th>Sugar / Cup</th><th>Water Content</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Watermelon (diced)</td><td>46</td><td>9g</td><td>92%</td></tr><tr><td>Strawberries</td><td>49</td><td>7g</td><td>91%</td></tr><tr><td>Peach (sliced)</td><td>60</td><td>13g</td><td>89%</td></tr><tr><td>Grapes</td><td>62</td><td>15g</td><td>81%</td></tr><tr><td>Apple (sliced)</td><td>65</td><td>13g</td><td>86%</td></tr><tr><td>Blueberries</td><td>84</td><td>15g</td><td>84%</td></tr><tr><td>Mango (diced)</td><td>107</td><td>23g</td><td>83%</td></tr><tr><td>Banana (sliced)</td><td>134</td><td>18g</td><td>75%</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr><h2>Hydration Benefits</h2><p>Besides being low in calories, watermelon's high water content helps keep you hydrated.</p><p>Eating watermelon contributes to daily fluid intake. While it shouldn't replace drinking water, watermelon can supplement hydration, especially during hot weather or physical activity.</p><p>Watermelon also has electrolytes like potassium, which help your body stay hydrated. The mix of water and electrolytes makes it a good snack after exercise.</p><p>For those who struggle to drink enough water, eating watermelon is a tasty way to help meet their hydration needs. Plus, it gives you nutrients that plain water doesn't have. Studies suggest that watermelon juice may reduce muscle soreness after exercise, attributed to an amino acid called citrulline, which watermelon contains in notable amounts.</p><hr><h2>Nutritional Content Beyond Calories</h2><p>Watermelon delivers more nutrition than you might expect from such a low-calorie fruit. Vitamin C is present in notable amounts, providing about 21% of daily needs per cup. This antioxidant vitamin supports immune function, skin health, and iron absorption.</p><p>Vitamin A provides approximately 18% of daily needs through beta-carotene and other carotenoids. These compounds support eye health and immune function.</p><p>Lycopene is the antioxidant that gives watermelon its red color, and watermelon has a lot of it. In fact, it has more lycopene per serving than raw tomatoes, which are usually known for this nutrient. Research suggests lycopene may help with heart health and cancer prevention.</p><p>Citrulline is an amino acid in watermelon that turns into arginine in your body. This may help with blood flow and exercise performance. Watermelon is one of the best sources of citrulline you can eat.</p><p>A cup of watermelon gives you about 5% of your daily potassium needs, which helps regulate blood pressure and supports muscle function.</p><div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Nutrient</th><th>Amount (1 cup)</th><th>% Daily Value</th><th>Key Benefit</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Vitamin C</td><td>~12mg</td><td>21%</td><td>Immune &amp; skin health</td></tr><tr><td>Vitamin A</td><td>~43mcg</td><td>18%</td><td>Eye &amp; immune health</td></tr><tr><td>Lycopene</td><td>6–7mg</td><td>—</td><td>Antioxidant, heart health</td></tr><tr><td>Potassium</td><td>~170mg</td><td>5%</td><td>Blood pressure &amp; muscles</td></tr><tr><td>Citrulline</td><td>~250mg</td><td>—</td><td>Blood flow &amp; exercise performance</td></tr><tr><td>Calories</td><td>46</td><td>—</td><td>Among lowest of all fruits</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr><h2>Different Ways to Enjoy Watermelon</h2><p>The most common way to eat watermelon is to cut it into chunks or slices and serve it fresh. This keeps all the nutrition and the crisp texture people love. Watermelon juice or smoothies have a stronger flavor but lose the fiber. A cup of juice has about the same calories as fresh watermelon, but it's easier to drink more, so watch your portions.</p><p>Frozen watermelon makes a sweet, refreshing snack. You can freeze chunks or make popsicles for a low-calorie alternative to ice cream.</p><p>Adding watermelon to salads brings sweetness and color to savory dishes. It goes especially well with feta cheese, mint, and balsamic reduction in summer salads.</p><p>Grilled watermelon is becoming more popular. A quick grill brings out its natural sweetness while keeping it refreshing.</p><p>Pickling watermelon rind turns what's usually thrown away into a tangy, crunchy topping. The rind has fewer calories than the red part and adds a unique texture to meals.</p><div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Preparation</th><th>Approx. Calories</th><th>Fiber Preserved</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Fresh chunks or slices</td><td>46 / cup</td><td>Yes</td><td>Best overall nutritional value</td></tr><tr><td>Juice or smoothie</td><td>~45 / cup</td><td>No</td><td>Easy to over-consume — watch portions</td></tr><tr><td>Frozen chunks or popsicles</td><td>46 / cup</td><td>Yes</td><td>Great low-cal frozen treat</td></tr><tr><td>Grilled watermelon</td><td>50–55 / cup</td><td>Yes</td><td>Natural sweetness enhanced</td></tr><tr><td>Watermelon salad</td><td>80–120 / cup</td><td>Yes</td><td>Depends on added ingredients</td></tr><tr><td>Pickled watermelon rind</td><td>~20 / cup</td><td>Moderate</td><td>Lower calorie, unique texture</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h2>Watermelon and Blood Sugar</h2><p>Even though watermelon is sweet, its effect on blood sugar is more complex than it seems.</p><p>Watermelon has a high glycemic index, around 72 to 80, which might worry people watching their blood sugar. But the glycemic index doesn't tell the whole story.</p><p>Glycemic load, which accounts for actual carbohydrate content per serving, tells a different story. Watermelon's glycemic load is only about 5 per serving, considered low. The high water content means each serving contains relatively little total carbohydrate. For most people, even those with diabetes, eating a moderate amount of watermelon doesn't cause big spikes in blood sugar. The important thing is to watch your portion size and see how your body reacts.</p><p>If you have diabetes or are concerned about blood sugar, pay attention to how your body responds to watermelon. Many people can enjoy normal portions without problems, but everyone is different.</p><div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Value</th><th>Context</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Glycemic Index (GI)</td><td>72–80</td><td>High by GI standards — often misunderstood</td></tr><tr><td>Glycemic Load (GL)</td><td>~5 per serving</td><td>LOW — the number that actually matters</td></tr><tr><td>Carbs per cup</td><td>11g</td><td>Below average for fruit</td></tr><tr><td>Sugar per cup</td><td>9g</td><td>Lower than grapes (15g) or banana (14g)</td></tr><tr><td>Suitable for diabetics?</td><td>In moderation</td><td>GL is low; portion control is key</td></tr><tr><td>Water dilution effect</td><td>High</td><td>High water content lowers real carb impact per bite</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr><h2>Watermelon for Weight Loss</h2><p>Watermelon has several benefits if you're trying to lose weight. You can eat satisfying portions for minimal calories. Feeling full matters for diet adherence, and watermelon provides volume without excessive calories. Watermelon's natural sweetness can help satisfy your sweet tooth without processed sugar. If you want something sweet, watermelon delivers real flavor with far fewer calories than candy, ice cream, or baked goods.</p><p>High water content promotes hydration, which supports metabolism and can reduce hunger. Watermelon doesn't have a lot of fiber—about 0.6 grams per cup—but it still helps with digestion and can make you feel a bit fuller. You can eat watermelon as a snack between meals, as a dessert instead of something heavier, or before meals to help you feel full before eating higher-calorie foods.</p><div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Weight Loss Advantage</th><th>Detail</th><th>Practical Impact</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Very low calorie density</td><td>46 cal/cup vs. ~200 cal for most snacks</td><td>Large, satisfying portions for few calories</td></tr><tr><td>High satiety from water</td><td>92% water fills your stomach</td><td>Reduces overall calorie intake</td></tr><tr><td>Natural sweetness</td><td>Satisfies sugar cravings</td><td>Replaces higher-calorie desserts</td></tr><tr><td>Hydration support</td><td>Contributes to daily fluid needs</td><td>Reduces false hunger signals</td></tr><tr><td>Citrulline content</td><td>~250mg per cup</td><td>Supports exercise performance &amp; fitness goals</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr><h2>Selecting and Storing Watermelon</h2><p>Picking a good watermelon helps you get the most enjoyment from this healthy fruit.</p><p>Look for a yellow spot on the bottom of the watermelon where it sat on the ground. This "field spot" means it's ripe. If the spot is white or pale green, the melon was picked too soon. Weight is important—a ripe watermelon should feel heavy for its size, which means it's full of water and juicy inside. You can also knock on the watermelon. A deep, hollow sound means it's ripe, while a higher sound might mean it's not ready yet. Store and consume within five days for the best quality.</p><p>Buying pre-cut watermelon is convenient, but it usually costs more and might not be as fresh as a whole melon you cut yourself.</p><p>While watermelon is low-calorie and healthy, excessive consumption can cause digestive distress because of its high water and fiber content. Eating a lot may cause bloating or loose stools. The natural sugars aren't a problem in normal amounts, but they add up if you eat several pounds. For most people, enjoying watermelon in reasonable amounts is just fine.</p><div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Selection Tip</th><th>What to Look For</th><th>Why It Matters</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Check the field spot</td><td>Yellow or creamy yellow patch on the bottom</td><td>Means it ripened fully on the vine</td></tr><tr><td>Feel the weight</td><td>Heavy for its size</td><td>More juice = more water &amp; sweetness inside</td></tr><tr><td>Knock test</td><td>Deep, hollow sound</td><td>Ripe; dull or thud sound = overripe</td></tr><tr><td>Inspect the skin</td><td>Firm, dull surface (not shiny)</td><td>Shiny skin often means picked too early</td></tr><tr><td>Store uncut</td><td>Room temperature up to 1 week</td><td>Preserves lycopene &amp; antioxidant content</td></tr><tr><td>Store cut</td><td>Refrigerated, consumed within 5 days</td><td>Keeps it fresh, safe, and flavorful</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Watermelon Calories</h2><h3>How much sugar is in watermelon?</h3><p>Watermelon contains about 9 grams of sugar per cup, which is lower than many other popular fruits. Grapes contain about 15 grams per cup, mangoes about 23 grams, and bananas about 14 grams. Watermelon tastes sweet due to its clean flavor profile, not exceptionally high sugar content. The high water content dilutes sugar concentration per bite.</p><h3>Is watermelon good before bed?</h3><p>Watermelon can be eaten at any time, though its high water content might increase nighttime trips to the bathroom. The sugar is low and usually won't affect your sleep. As a low-calorie evening snack, watermelon is a great choice.</p><h3>Does watermelon burn fat?</h3><p>No food, including watermelon, actually burns fat. But watermelon can help with weight loss because it's sweet, filling, and low in calories, so it can take the place of higher-calorie foods. Citrulline in watermelon may also help with exercise, which supports fitness goals. Watermelon is good for weight loss, but it's not a miracle fat burner.</p><h3>Can you eat the white part of watermelon?</h3><p>The white part between the green skin and red flesh of watermelon is edible and healthy. It has citrulline, fiber, and some vitamins. It tastes milder and is crunchier than the red part. Many cultures pickle or cook the rind instead of throwing it away. Eating the white part helps reduce waste and adds nutrition.</p><p>Heading to a summer gathering? CalorieVision's AI-powered photo analysis can instantly calculate the calories in your watermelon serving. Simply snap a photo and get accurate nutritional information in seconds.</p><p><strong>Try CalorieVision free</strong> and enjoy summer's favorite fruit with complete confidence.</p><hr><h2>The Bottom Line</h2><p>Watermelon contains approximately 46 calories per cup, making it one of the lowest-calorie fruits you can eat. Its high water content—about 92%—keeps the calories so low while still providing hydration and nutrients, including Vitamin C, the antioxidant lycopene, and the amino acid citrulline. These nutrients make watermelon genuinely beneficial rather than simply "allowed" because it's low-calorie.</p><p>Whether you want to manage your weight, cool off in the summer, or just enjoy a tasty fruit, watermelon is a great pick. Its low calories let you eat plenty without guilt, so you can satisfy your hunger and sweet tooth. And now you know exactly why it deserves its place in healthy eating.</p></div>$body$,
    'published',
    true,
    'en',
    '2026-01-15T22:53:28.195+00:00',
    '2026-01-15T22:53:28.195+00:00',
